{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between request-construction and API client payload wiring. A unit test of only a formatter could miss dropped/overwritten fields during module integration. Higher levels are not required because behavior text is about payload contents, not real network behavior or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module to a fake in-process API transport, invoke classification, and assert the captured outbound request contains every configured taxonomy label exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at parser/normalizer/module boundary: API response value must flow through validation before caller output. Unit-only validation logic could miss incorrect wiring of response extraction. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text focusing on post-response mapping logic, not live provider or model quality.","test_description":"Use an in-process fake API returning an out-of-taxonomy label (e.g., \"medical\"); call classify and assert returned value is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.45,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior explicitly isolates normalization determinism for identical raw responses; this is a local pure transformation boundary with no required module interaction or I/O.","test_description":"Call normalization function multiple times with the same raw response fixture and assert identical final label each run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior text requires repeated live API calls and consistency of returned label under real provider/model behavior. Mocked model outputs would hide true variability/non-determinism. Workflow is not required because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N real classification calls for the same input against the live provider, record provider raw responses and final labels, and assert label changes only when provider response materially changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is interaction between token-budget logic and dispatch gate (whether request is sent or blocked/transformed). Unit tests of token counting alone can miss accidental dispatch despite over-budget input. Higher levels are disqualified because enforcement is explicitly pre-dispatch.","test_description":"Configure a small token budget, use a fake API client, pass an over-budget document, and assert policy outcome (truncate or reject) plus whether dispatch was correctly blocked/allowed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.33,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This behavior depends on real AI API execution and provider-reported usage accounting; stubs can trivially satisfy budget and miss real provider/tokenizer behavior. System was considered, but behavior text ties correctness to live provider model usage metrics from an AI API call, which keeps Agentic as minimum.","test_description":"Execute real classification calls with representative documents and assert provider-reported token usage fields remain <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.64,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure is retry orchestration across modules (error mapping, wait policy, retry attempt), which is catchable with in-process fakes and controlled clock/timer hooks. Higher levels are disqualified because behavior text targets reaction to rate-limit signal, not real provider model output quality.","test_description":"Use a fake API that returns rate-limit error first then success; assert module waits according to retry policy, retries, and returns successful label instead of surfacing immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
